<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5309&amp;p=48177#p48177</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5309&amp;p=48177#p48177"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Of all the 8/16 bit machines, which one to code for?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5309&amp;p=48177#p48177"><![CDATA[
It depends on what you mean by "almost identical to NES".<br /><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>A palette divided into smaller sections, where each part of a background plane has an "attribute" that designates which section of the palette will be used: Widespread. </li><li>Pixel-mapped background plane with attributes, where attribute clash becomes a significant issue: Seen in at least Apple II, ZX Spectrum, and Super Game Boy. </li><li>Tile-mapped background plane with attribute areas larger than a tile: Unique to the NES as far as I can tell. </li></ol><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Mon Jun 22, 2009 1:59 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
